{{Infobox person | name = Ernst Posner | image = Photograph of Ernst Posner.png | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Ernst Maximilian Posner | birth_date = {{Birth date|1892|08|09}} | birth_place = [[Berlin]], [[Germany]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1980|04|18|1892|08|09}} | death_place = Germany | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Archivist; Historian | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Ernst Maximilian Posner''' (9 August 1892 - 18 April 1980) was a Prussian state archivist and a professor of history and archival science at [[American University]] in Washington.<ref name=Ross1981>{{Citation | title = Ernst Posner: The Bridge between the Old World and the New | url = http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015072453122;view=1up;seq=318 | year = 1981 | last = Ross | first= Rodney A. | journal = The American Archivist | pages = 304–312 | volume = 44 | issue = 4 | accessdate = 2015-04-18 }}</ref><ref name="Eckert2012">{{cite book|first=Astrid M. |last=Eckert|title=The Struggle for the Files: The Western Allies and the Return of German Archives After the Second World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vRjJVlRG4qcC&pg=PA118|accessdate=30 July 2013|date=2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-88018-3}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Posner was born into an upper-middle class academic family of [[History of Jews in Germany|Jewish heritage]]. After attending the [[University of Berlin]], he served the [[Imperial German Army]] in [[World War I]] on both the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern]] and [[Western Front (World War I)|Western]] fronts, suffering a severe injury in [[Poland]] on December 1915.<ref name="Mommsen">Mommsen, Wolfgang A. ''Ernst Posner, Mittler zwischen deutschem und amerikanischem Archivwesen. Zu seinem 75. Geburtstag''. Der Archivar 20 (3), 1967, pp. 217-230.</ref> After the war, he finished his dissertation at the University of Berlin.<ref name=Ross1981/>
== Career in Germany == Posner began his professional career working for the Prussian State Privy Archive in 1921.<ref name="Eckert2012"/> Although exempt from the 1933 civil service laws as a World War I veteran, Posner was fired from the Prussian State Archives in 1935 as a result of the [[Nuremberg Laws]], and interned in the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] in November 1938, after the [[Kristallnacht]].<ref name="LehmannSheehan2002">{{cite book|first1=Hartmut|last1=Lehmann|first2=James J.|last2=Sheehan|title=An Interrupted Past: German-Speaking Refugee Historians in the United States after 1933|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O5WNhrmBVY0C&pg=PA75|accessdate=30 July 2013|date=1991|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-40326-X|pages=75}}</ref>
== Career in the United States == In 1939, Posner and his wife Käthe managed to flee to the [[United States]] via [[Sweden]]. With help from archivist [[Solon Buck]], he began teaching archival administration at [[American University]] in 1940, and remained there for 21 years.<ref name=Ross1981/> A 1943 lecture of Posner's (later published as "Public Records under Military Occupation") was among the first calls for plans to administer captured German records.<ref name="Eckert2012"/> In November 1944, Posner prepared a report on the German archival profession, including biographical sketches and estimates of political views, for 72 leading German archivists.<ref name="Eckert2012"/>{{rp|108}} For his role in the development of American archival theory and practice, he was sometimes called "the Dean of American archivists."<ref name=Ross1981/> From 1955 to 1956 Posner served as the 11th president of the [[Society of American Archivists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www2.archivists.org/history/leaders/presidents|title = Presidents: Society of American Archivists|date = 2014|accessdate = August 14, 2014|publisher = Society of American Archivists}}</ref>
In 1972, Posner returned to Europe, settling in [[Wiesbaden]], Germany.<ref>{{NDB|20|652|653|Posner, Ernst Maximilian|Eckhart G. Franz|137541341}}</ref>
== Selected Publications<ref name="Epstein1993">{{cite book|first=Catherine |last=Epstein|title=A Past Renewed: A Catalog of German-Speaking Refugee Historians in the United States After 1933|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fYoxYd3A-fsC&pg=PA249|accessdate=30 July 2013|date= 1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44063-9|pages=249}}</ref> == * ''Drei Vorträge zum Archivwesen der Gegenwart''. Stockholm: Alb. Bonnier, 1940 * ''American state archives''. Chicago; London: University of Chicago Press, 1964 * ''Archives & the public interest: selected essays''. Washington: Public Affairs Press, 1967 * ''Archives in the ancient world''. Cambridge, Mass.: Harvard University Press, 1972. {{ISBN|9780674044630}}
== Honors == * Since 1983, the [[Society of American Archivists]] has been awarding the ''Ernst Posner Prize'' for an "outstanding essay dealing with some facet of archival administration, history, theory, and/or methodology that was published during the preceding year in The American Archivist."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archivists.org/governance/handbook/section12-posner |title=Fellows' Ernst Posner Award |author= |date= |website= |publisher=Society of American Archivists |accessdate=27 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226105723/http://www2.archivists.org/governance/handbook/section12-posner |archivedate=26 December 2013 |df= }}</ref> * The Ernst Posner building at the German National Archives in Berlin is named after Posner.<ref>[https://www.bundesarchiv.de/bundesarchiv/dienstorte/berlin_lichterfelde/ Bundesarchiv, Berlin-Lichterfelde]</ref>
